{
  "doc_id": "28373",
  "text": "A retrospective analysis of small series of patients reported a response rate that is between 13 and 46 % in patients treated with enzalutamide after docetaxel, with lower treatment duration, PFS and OS that in reported second line randomised trials [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . In one study, the authors reported that prior response to docetaxel and abiraterone did not predict response to enzalutamide [CITATION_4] . However, another group reported that higher PSA-responses were observed among abiraterone-sensitive patients (44 %) than in abiraterone-insensitive patients (16 %) [CITATION_5] . Overall, enzalutamide seemed to retain its clinical activity in patients who had progressed to prior abiraterone and docetaxel, and it is not clear whether abiraterone resistance predicts enzalutamide benefits.",
